segments.text: Interviewing Dr. Newton Ellis, head of the Department of Industrial Engineering.
Today's date is July 29, 1981.
Dr. Ellis, could we begin by you telling us something about your personal background, where you grew up?
Well, I was born in Texas.
I was born in Northeast Texas.
But I grew up pretty much all over the U.S. My dad bought a construction.
And as a result, I lived in several states and went to several schools, sometimes as many as a half a dozen to a dozen different schools in one year.
Where were you born in?
I was born in Paris, Texas.
Where were some of the states that you lived in?
Well, most of the states were southwest states, picking up from probably as far west as Arizona.
It was coming around to New Mexico, and then to Louisiana, Arkansas, Tennessee.
It was for some time briefly in New Jersey and New York.
I'm from Louisiana.
I've heard you live in Louisiana.
I'm from the amendment which is 30 miles east of there.
When did you graduate from high school and where?
I graduated from high school in 1950 from Texas City High School.
You had an interest in mathematics and engineering as a student?
As a high school student, I was very much interested in engineering, math, quantitative aspects of education.
That's one of the reasons I wound up at Texas A&M.
When you graduated in 1950, you went to Texas A&M as a student?
I came to Texas A&M as a freshman.
I was majoring in industrial engineering, spent three years here, and became intrigued with the human side of engineering.
Industrial engineering was the closest to that, but it didn't quite have what I thought I was interested in.
That's one of the reasons I didn't finish my degree.
What did you do after you left here?

Well after, I spent about three years, in fact I was in my senior year, and I had a long talk with the wind department about my interests that were more focused in respect to people and less focused in the areas of engineering.
And he recommended that I probably ought to look into a different curriculum.
Not knowing a whole lot about the curriculums that might be available.
which focused me on the human being.
Someone told me about psychology and I transferred to Baylor and picked up a major in psychology.
I finished there in 1956.
Okay, what were some of the, since you moved around so much in your boyhood, what are some of the things you remember about that?
Well, did you find that every place was pretty much the same, or did you find that there was a lot of differences?
I found there was a lot of differences.
I guess that was really my first brush.
Again, I was very young still, but it was my first brush at problems associated with, or that had racial overtones associated with it.
Areas of...
Northeast Texas and into Louisiana, there was a great problem, I would say, with the standpoint of the lights.
I got into Tennessee, and there was a problem associated with the, again, I don't know the exact terminology, so I'll say the hillbilly element.
That may not be the proper terminology, but it had those types of overtones.
I also lived in California, I forgot to mention that.
California also was going at that particular time, as I recall it, was the first years of integration.
And I remember quite a few problems associated with integration with the school system in San Diego.
And I would say that traveling around gave me a better understanding of the people.
I probably wouldn't have gained by moving in a single area and growing up in a single area.
That was probably the main contribution.
Other than that, it's seeing some of the different things that existed in different parts of the U.S.
In 1956, when you graduated from Baylor with a bachelor's in psychology, what did you do then?
Well, I thought I was ready to
enter into something that tied engineering and psychology together.
You mean something like efficiency engineering?
Well, after the fact, I would say this was 56, about 60 really the field of engineering psychology began to emerge.
Prior to that, I guess I was before my time,
I took a job that I really couldn't find a job I was interested in.
I discovered that if you do anything with a psychology degree, you need a graduate degree.
So I took a job in Temco Aircraft as the payroll department, payroll insurance department.
I ran the night shift.
Where?
At Grand Prairie.
And it was there that having that job permitted me to initiate
I'm trying to protect this Christian university.
I wound up getting a master's degree and a PhD degree, but during the process, about 61, aerospace was beginning to catch on.
An emerging field column at that time called engineering psychology was beginning to catch on in aerospace.
It was a technology that was to deal with trying to design equipment to fit the person, to fit the pilot.
It was called engineering psychology.
We transitioned then to another thing called human engineering.
And over the years, eventually transitioned into a field called human factors engineering.
So I was perfectly trained in engineering and in psychology.
It was a perfect marriage between my training and my interest.
Consequently, that was the reason.
spent the time in aerospace after graduation.
When did you complete your master's?
I completed my master's in 62 and I completed my PhD in 64.
Both at TCU?
Both at TCU.
The reason for that, I was employed at LTV at the time where I transitioned to Temco, Chance Fault.
I worked at the Leintemko vintage in Leintemko-Bach, the transition companies.
Is it still called Leintemko-Bach?
No, it's called LTB.
They dropped the full use of names and just used initials.
I spent 10 years with them.
Okay, then that brings us to 1964.
What did you do then?
Well, I was employed.
At the same time I was working on a degree, I was employed.
I was in a program that permitted me to work in the school.
And I was working in the, I believe it was called Human Engineering and Safety Department.
When I finished my degree in 64, I had the opportunity to go back to where I was, or stay in the department.
I was going to go to a new development department in this space.
Astronautics Division, where the emphasis would be placed on designing equipment not for the pilot, but for the astronaut.
And I felt like that was at the cutting edge of technology, and I chose to go with the Astronautics Division.
I spent the next two years or so there, and worked on some space systems.

the design team that worked on some of the spacesuits, some of the Jiminy, early Jiminy space missions, and the development of what was called an astronaut maneuvering unit, something that permitted the astronaut to buckle on or secure to his back, a la Buck Rogers style, and get out of the vehicle and motor around through space.
It was one of the Jiminy missions.
This was while you were still at LTV?
Yes.
Okay, you stayed there until 1969?
No, I left there.
I had an opportunity to move up.
It must have been 1960...
I'll say 66, somewhere in that vicinity.
I took a job at a senior scientist of a small research group called Life Sciences Incorporated.
It was a high technology research group having to do with human behavior as it related to complex hardware systems.
And I spent back time until I came in.
I was there a couple of years.
I don't recall exactly how long.
A couple of years or so.
It was a small group, probably having about 25 employees and all of them PhDs.
And we probably did about a half million dollar business.
And LTV,
with a big program developing in LTV about 68, I think I was in life sciences two years.
And they came and asked me to come back, take a special job in advanced systems.
It had to do with being a part of a special group of engineers that were to try to define aerospace systems of the future.
That intrigued me.
I came back to it.
Okay, Dr. Ellis, would you discuss your coming to Texas A&M in 1969, please?
Well, I was right in the middle of a major proposal after LTV, and I received a telephone call from a Bill Wortham.
He told me he was head of the Department of Industrial Engineering at Texas A&M.
He caught me at a bad time because, like I said, we were in a proposal effort.
It had been going on for about three months.
We'd probably been spending about 60 hours a week or more in that proposal effort.
He caught me right as we were beginning to close out, and he caught me at a bad time.
And he said he wanted to talk to me about the possibility of a job, a teaching job at Texas A&M.
I told him that I wasn't interested in a teaching job at Texas A&M and that he had caught me at a bad time and I basically appreciated it but he didn't keep me and I sort of cut him off.
But he was a persistent person and he called me back.
At this time we had finished the proposal effort and I was in a slow down period and was in a much better mood.
He was a good salesman too.
He talked to me about some of the things he was trying to do at Texas A&M.
And Bill Wortham turned out to be a person that had come from the Dallas area from Texas Instruments.
And he was up to speed on what I considered some of the newer developing engineering technologies at the time.
One of them happened to be human factors engineering, and he said he was trying to develop an industrial engineering department that would emphasize these.
He talked about maintainability, reliability, safety, and he said, I'm looking for someone to help us in the human factors field, and I've been told you're it.
I told him I really wasn't.
Well, I had in the back of my mind the idea of coming to
into university sometime to teach, but this was not the time.
I was very comfortable with where I was.
I'd just come back to LTV and been there probably a year or a little less.
I can't remember exactly.
I told him I really wasn't interested in a teaching job at this time, maybe two or three years.
He said, well, why don't you just come down and visit?
Take a look at what we've got here.
Let's talk.
Well, he called me the time we had just finished that proposal.
I didn't have a whole lot to do.
I was in between sort of projects.
I was trying to catch up on some needed rest anyway.
And I said, well, as long as there's no obligation, if you realize that, I'll be glad to come down.
I've got some extra time.
And I came down and spent a couple of days.
And I was sold immediately.
Bill Wortham was a good salesman.
But more than that, I was sold on Texas A&M.
I was sold on what the department was doing.
And I was immediately caught up in the potential that existed.
My wife's from over in Somerville.
She was spending the day over there.
We came back and we went through College Station.
She said, you know, I could never live here.
I always lived in the Dallas area.
She said, you could never live in a small community like this.
I hope you didn't get interested, weren't interested in a job.
And I didn't tell her that I was until we got back to Dallas.
And a couple of days later, I told her I was interested in that job.
She said, oh, no, I don't think we could live down there.
Bryan College Station was much smaller then than it is now.
To make a long story short, she said, I'd like to go back down.
So we came back down.
At the time, I think there was about three houses available in the whole community to look at.
And they were building.
Oaks out here, and was actually building a house that she was sort of interested in.
Anyway, we came back, and she said, well, of course, if I wanted to come, she certainly would like to come with me and learn about that.
But she made the deal.
She said, well, I'll tell you what.
You'll purchase a house like we have here, and you'll always get season tickets to all the sporting events.
She's a big sports fan.
Maybe I'll, not kidding me, she said, maybe I can move with you.
And of course, it wound up we did.
And she just immediately fell in love with the community.
She just didn't realize, not living here at the time, what was really available in the small community.
There's a more cohesiveness.
Merchants were more willing to help you.
Banks were more willing to
make that personal touch.
And my daughter was just going into junior high.
She immediately, sometime during that year, said, I'm going to Texas A&M.
Well, you know, that hurt her.
She'll change her mind many times before that, but she didn't.
She never wavered.
And she graduated last year.
But that's how we came.
Bill Wortham...
insisted that I come down and I was very much intrigued with him, the department.
I got to meet Dean Benson while I was here.
I was very much impressed with him as an individual and I was just caught up in the potential that existed.
And what was the position that you took when you came here?
I had not had any teaching experience.
They told me that I would have to start as an assistant professor, but that I would be promoted fairly quickly.
That's what happened.
But I came as an assistant professor in industrial engineering and as a researcher with the Texas Transportation Institute, a joint appointment, research and teaching.
And you held that until you became department head?
No, there's quite a bit of development and change in there.
Of course, I was promoted to associate professor the second year.
I think I served a system for up to two years.
During the process of research at TTI, which is part of the engineering experiment station, I was able to
sell the then directoratees of TTI, Jack Keyes, on the need to emphasize the driver in transportation research.
TTI had built an image and an excellent reputation on what you might call the hardware, the cement, the bridges, the roadways, the things.
But it never had a real emphasis on the driver as part of the transportation system.
And due to my experience and interest,
and sort of sold him on the idea.

Sometimes, three years later, four years later, I'm not sure about the exact time, he, due to my somewhat success in developing research in that area, he developed a program, TTI, associated with the driver.
I can't remember the name of the program.
Highway Traffic Safety Programs.
And I was the program manager.
We started with about myself and about three people.
And within two years, we were about 30 people.
And we then organized the division TTI set up
with an umbrella over I think there were five divisions of research.
One being highways and structures and bridges and so forth.
And the sixth division was formed having to do with human factors and systems engineering.
And I became the division head of that particular division.
And it was
Again, it was TTI's first emphasis in the area of research associated with the driver and the transportation element.
That was actually when I developed my
I guess the development of the research side of my personality, Texas A&M.
In the meantime, the department was growing and there was the idea of trying to have a human factors engineering division in the department at the graduate level.
That was organized somewhere during the time and I was made division in that.
That sort of takes me up through
at the time that there was a change.
Actually, we had two changes in department heads.
Bill Wortham stepped down and eventually left.
Paul Newell was department head for, it seemed like, about three years.
And when he stepped down, that's when I became department head.
What was that?
Seventy-five.
Could you explain briefly?
in layman's terms, what an industrial engineer does on the job?
I'm not as competent, probably, in defining what industrial engineering does, per se, because my training and experience was in probably an auxiliary area of the field.

But primarily industrial engineering is a technology that tries to optimize the relationships between the hardware that's necessary to produce a product and the person that's necessary to run the hardware that's to produce the product.
An industrial engineer is a part of that.
He's the engineer that facilitates the relationship between man, machine, and resources such that you can produce a product.
Efficiency engineer is a type of industrial engineer.
the quality control, the constant overview of the planning and the manufacturing process, the management engineer, all that fits the industrial engineering.
How many faculty members do you have in the department?
You mean the number of people in the classroom?
Just under your supervision in this particular department?
Well, again, that's
In terms of the number of people it takes to teach our classes, we probably run close to 100.
But in terms of full-time faculty that are assistant professors and above, I think we have 61.
And we have to pull in people from other parts of the university.
We use our own students just to teach the classes, do the size of the program.
About how many students do you have enrolled for a degree in industrial engineering?
Well, let me say something about industrial engineering.
Industrial engineering is, I guess, is probably the only department in the university, if not the only.
I can't think of any others like it.
I think it's the only department that administers five different degree programs.
This department administers the computer science program, the industrial engineering program, the bioengineering program, the safety engineering program, and the industrial hygiene program.
Each one of those has its own set of faculty, its own set of students, but it's administered under the umbrella of one department, industrial engineering.
Okay, now within that,
on those total programs, there's just under 1,800 students.
306 of those are graduate students.
About 80 of those graduate students are Ph.D. students.
How long had you been offering a Ph.D. degree in industrial engineering?
That goes back before my time, so I really couldn't tell you that.
must have been somewhere in the early 60s.
The only degree program, the new degree program that's been instituted since I've been department head is the Bioengineering Master's and Ph.D. program and that must have been about 75 and the
safety engineering program, undergraduate and master's program, which is probably about two years old.
Well, PhD in computer science began in 1969.
I don't know if there were some other ones before that.
Yes, there were.
The IE program is much older than that.
I just don't know when it was.
I would say that probably either the early 60s or maybe even the late 50s.
Could you comment on the quality of the students enrolled in this department, particularly referring to the incoming students?
Well, I think that as the statistics show, the quality of the incoming student has been improving over the last six or seven years of growth.
We're getting a better student now.
There's no doubt about that.
We're not only getting more students, actually more than we can really handle, but we are getting a better student as well.
I know the board yesterday, the past day, at least agreed to some kind of role in management policy that would upgrade the standards
in terms of SAT scores for students before you finish your high school class.
But even here, I'm not sure that's going to affect the growth in engineering that much because we've been getting a very, very good student the last few years anyway.
That would seem to contradict the public perception of the news media that the quality of students is declining.
Do you find that the case?
Well, I can only say overall, all the statistics would show that there is, if you look at the reports on standardized test scores, there's some kind of decline nationwide.
But if you compare what we're getting here, our SAT scores are above the standard.
I'm not sure exactly what it is, but you can report it.
The engineering people that I've interviewed here have concurred in that assessment.
All the others have seen it, too.
Do you have any figures on the number of women in the program of the 1,800 students?
Just an estimate.
Other than the fact that we have the largest percentage of women in any of the industrial engineering departments, I honestly can't give you that estimate.
Would you say it's under 10% or over?
No, it's over.
But under 20?
I'd say that it's over 20.
I think that the...
I could look at that right quick.
We just need a rough estimate.
Maybe a four.
I would say somewhere, yeah, I would say that.
Probably 25%.
Okay, so industrial engineering attracts more women than the other fields of engineering.
Yes.
All right.
Do you have any idea of why that might be the case?
Well, again, included in this department are those technologies that relate more to the human element of engineering.
Safety engineering, bioengineering, industrial engineering.
Industrial engineering has always, in the past, been known as the management engineering field.
As such, I really think that human element is what attracts more women
Do you have any figures on the number of black steels that grow in this department?
No.
Again, we probably, percentage-wise, have more than the other departments, but we just don't have those figures.
Is it under 5%?
Yes.
Do you have any idea why relatively few blacks enroll in engineering here?
This seems to be a situation throughout all the departments.
Yeah, I think that the black student typically does not get introduced to some of the quantitative and physical sciences emphasis in the high schools.
as typically the white student does.
Engineering is a tougher curriculum.
You don't quite have the background at the time to get into it.
The failure rate's high, and there's less of a tendency to get involved in something that isn't high-productively failure.
Do you have any statistics on what your dropout rate or attrition rate is in industrial engineering?
I mean, what percent of the people who start the program never complete it?
We're pretty much on the same college.
I actually forgot what that is.
I forgot what that percentage is.
Did you get that from any of the other department heads?
The other engineering department people have been saying that roughly half who began never complete.
It's about a 50-50 situation.
They're about as likely to finish as they're not.
That's what the others have found.
I think that's probably right.
I think it probably is a little bit more than that, though, in that I'd say probably 60% finish.
That's been steadily improving, or slightly improving over the last few years.
At least the college has given us that data.
What about the job prospects of people with bachelor's degrees in industrial engineering?
It's never been better.
What salary can they expect starting out with a bachelor's degree?

Well, I would say you're talking about, again, there's a range here, depending if the person's had a co-op experience, in grades and things like that, but I would say that you're talking about a low end of the spectrum of probably $19,000 a year in the upper range of something like
This is last year's.
Is it higher for a master's or a doctorate?
Yes.
How much?
Oh, again, because a person with a master's degree will have other experience normally.
But let's assume that there's just no experience that's gone straight through.
There's no additional experience.
You're talking about probably
another $2,000 for a master's degree, an annual, and you're probably talking about maybe $5,000.
What are some of the firms that hire industrial engineers?
By name or by?
If you could give us that, just to give an idea, because the average person probably doesn't have any idea where an industrial engineer works.
Well, more recently, the oil companies have come in and been sort of purchasing the industrial engineer.
planning and decision making purposes.
But typically they have been all the manufacturing industries.
Steel, metal cutting, aerospace.
Again, mostly the manufacturing.
Most of the graduates of the program have several job opportunities to pick from.
I would say that typically you're talking about probably six to seven offers per student.
Regarding the industrial engineering department, do you have any idea on how many universities across the nation offer programs in this field?
Yeah, about 140.
It's a lot of them.
Do you have any idea on how the A&M program ranks others nationwide?
Well, according to all the...
There's several ranking sources in what's called the Dorman Report, which is one a lot of people look at.
We rank 10th in the nation.
In the...
American Society of Engineering Education rankings, they rank you on several different categories in terms of faculty quality, amount of research, amount of resources.
There's about five different places they rank you, and we're in the top five.
Normally any one of those.
Sometimes we're number one, sometimes we're always number five.
We're typically in the top five in the way the ASEE ranks.
What is ASEE?
American Society of Engineering Education.
Is the faculty considered your strong point in your program?
Faculty and our research departments.
Where are some of the schools that the faculty members are from?
Well, Mr. Black, you name it.
We have some from around our own area, the University of Texas, Arkansas, taking into account some of those numbers.

Texas, outside Texas, we've got people from the University of Oklahoma, we've got people from Oklahoma State, we've got people from Purdue, University of Michigan, Penn State, University of Pittsburgh.
You're teaching faculty members whole PhDs?
All of what we consider our senior faculty members on the Ph.D. What are some of the weaknesses, if any, of the program?
Well, at the current time, problems are associated with space and just to handle students.
We have been teaching those.
We're having to handle students
put more students in laboratories than you've got facilities in.
That damages the quality of your teaching.
When you have to put more students in a classroom, a faculty member is accustomed to really handle the standpoint of trying to teach engineering.
That's a problem.
The last three years or so, we've faced situations where we just don't have enough classrooms, we don't have enough faculty.
What about funding from the state legislature for industrial engineering?
Is there enough, do you consider it funding to be adequate?
In terms of, our funding from the legislature comes in two ways, faculty salaries and department operating money.
The problems that we're experiencing now is that we stay two years behind the growth curve.
We're funded on a biennial basis in the state so that money we're getting in any one time is basically behind.
And if you're not in a growth mode, everything's fine.
And I would say that we're happy to fund it.

But in these periods of growth where we've been saved by hand, our funds have not been, we have not been added to the funding in terms of the growth, in terms of the way the budget operates in the state.
Do you have any figures on what your department budget is for this year?
Yeah, I do.
I can't add that to the plan.
Okay.
Okay.
Actually, the reason I can't say that because I don't, they really don't pass the budget.
Well, for the past year.
Well, the past year, yes.
In terms of our academic money, we had, in the Department of Law, we had $1.8 million.
Okay.
What about sources of funding for research programs?
What's the sources of those?
We run, for the past five years, have been one of the major...
departments of economy and engineering in terms of research, dollar volume produced.
We run about 2 million a year.
And our sources are fairly well divided in terms of state sources and federal sources.
And then I would say that one's about 40%, 40%, and there's about 20% that we've picked up local industry, or industry sources.
One of those specific examples of industry, we have been funded by General Dynamics, LTV,
and some smaller manufacturing companies.
I can't recall the names now.
From a state standpoint, we have been funded for research by cities.
El Paso, Arlington, some of our major contributors.
We've developed the software systems for them.
From the standpoint of, we've also received the funds from some of the state agencies.
One of the governor's offices.
We've received some research from Texas Education Agency.
Going to the federal level, we receive funds from the National Science Foundation, Department of Defense, Department of Energy.
That's sort of what's matter.
Could you discuss, Dr. Ellis, specifically some of the research endeavors that are now underway or that have recently been completed?
Well, I'll probably touch on the ones that are
or most interesting, which we have probably made a name for ourselves nationally and internationally.
And that is in the, and that is an ongoing research program that started about five years ago and will be continuing the next five years, I believe.
It's an area in which we have some of my faculty applying engineering techniques to try to understand food-bearing plants.

The idea is that we can apply engineering techniques to understand and model and describe how a plant that bears food actually operates given the conditions in which it exists, whether it's water, sunlight, how it uses nutrients, and so forth.
We feel like then we can tell the person in the agricultural field how to optimize or increase food production.
It's a rather unique, ingenious approach that says I can look at a plant, a food plant, just like I look at a manufacturing facility.
If I can describe it mathematically well enough, then I can tell you what you need to change to make that plant produce better.
And it has caught the attention of people at the national and international level.
We have several faculty.
There's no food conference given even internationally.
Some of our faculty are not always invited to give presentations and so forth.
That's probably the area in which, well, one other area also connected to engineering applied to problems that you may not think that they would be applied to.
And also using the techniques to model the growth and spread of insects that are damaging the crops.
Ways to detect them.
how to sample them to describe their spread, and then how to optimize the use of pesticides to stop the spread.
I guess the major project being in the Pine Parkville area.
The insect is quite damaging to the pine and lumber industry.
That's an area in which we have made quite an impact.
Now, outside of that, we have the typical areas that we normally do research in.
We do part of the research and manufacturing area.
We have a person that recently developed a computerized model for describing and understanding the modular manufacturing process.
It has been introduced and being used by several industries.
We cooperate with Texas Transportation Institute in the study of the driver.
One of our faculty has been involved in the state-of-the-art study of providing a real-time information display system to the highway, interstate highway.
Those are the three major projects that have gone on and are still going on right now.
There's a multiplicity of smaller ones.
Are these projects done by faculty members and graduate students?
Yes sir.
Where do they conduct their research?
Well, if it's the modeling research, this is sort of a paper-pencil-computer approach with field data.
Some of the field data is collected in cooperation with the College of Agriculture.
This is engineering agriculture studies.
And some of the field data is collected right now on people's farms, meadows, and so forth.
Tele-type back into the computer communications.
Obviously the highway type stuff is done with TTI facilities either out of the annex, but some of the facilities are in the actual context of the roadway, Houston, Dallas, and so forth.
How many of your faculty members have joint appointments through TTI in addition to being on the teaching faculty?
Well, this will vary as a function of research needs at TTI, but any given semester we'll probably be sharing about three faculty at TTI.
Let me switch the tape just a second.
The last thing I want to ask you about is the changes that you've seen here since you were a student in the early 50s and since you came in 69 up to this time.
So just a broad change that you've seen.
